# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chart-junk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Markings and visual elements can be called chartjunk if they are not part of the minimum set of visuals necessary to communicate the information understandably.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Another kind of chartjunk skews the depiction and makes it difficult to understand the real data being displayed.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Examples of this type include items depicted out of scale to one another, noisy backgrounds making comparison between elements difficult in a chart or graph, and 3-D simulations in line and bar charts.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] The term *chartjunk* was coined by Edward Tufte in his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* based on ideas and materials developed for a Princeton statistics course co-taught with John Tukey.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] The term has been associated with Tufte in other references.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] In *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* Tufte claims that good design is founded in minimalist design principles.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Specifically, he states that "graphics reveal data" if they are designed with "graphical integrity." Tufte, through minimalist design principles, was committed to an objective and neutral values of science.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Other researchers have argued that minimalism is not objective and is full of its own rhetoric and potential to bias.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Tufte, in coining the term chartjunk, also made direct comments about a well-known designer at that time, Nigel Holmes.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] This debate between Tufte and Holmes is emblematic of the tension between statistical and designerly approaches to visualization design.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] The term chartjunk is an umbrella term that can be used to describe a variety of visual devices and has been referenced by different terms across research.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Alternative terms include *embellishment,* *excessive annotation*, decoration, *extraneous elements*, and *unnecessary ornamentation*.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] Robert Kosara, also a data visualization practitioner, researcher, and author of the blog EagerEyes, noted that not all chartjunk are the same, some are harmful (e.g. a busy background), others harmless (e.g. nice borders or pictures), and some even helpful (e.g. annotations).
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] In a recent study by Parsons and Shukla, they interviewed data visualization designers and found that there is both a "corrective movement" in the design community to move away from minimalist design principles, but also, that designers had different definitions for what constitutes chartjunk.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] The information visualization research community has researched the effects of chartjunk on how viewers interpret visualizations.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] There have been studies that found that chartjunk increases long-term memorability of the chart.
[src:chart-junk/chartjunk] A recent study found that chartjunk, in the form of semantically meaningful icons, increased accessibility of charts for people with Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities (IDD).
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Edward Rolf Tufte was born in 1942 in Kansas City, Missouri, to Virginia Tufte (1918–2020) and Edward E.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He grew up in Beverly Hills, California, where his father was a longtime city official.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He graduated from the public Beverly Hills High School.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte received a BS and a MS in statistics from Stanford University, and a Doctor of Philosophy in political science from Yale University.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] His dissertation was completed in 1968 and titled *The Civil Rights Movement and Its Opposition*.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte was hired in 1967 by the Woodrow Wilson School of Princeton University as a lecturer in politics and public affairs, where he steadily moved up to the rank of full Professor in 1972.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He taught courses there in political economy and data analysis while publishing three quantitatively inclined political science books.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In 1975, while at Princeton, Tufte was asked to teach a statistics course to a group of journalists who were visiting the school to study economics.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He developed a set of readings and lectures on statistical graphics, which he further developed in joint seminars he taught with renowned statistician John Tukey, a pioneer in the field of information design.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] These course materials became the foundation for Tufte's first book on information design, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In 1977, Tufte left Princeton University for Yale University, where he accepted an appointment as Professor of Political Science, Statistics, and Computer Science, as well as a Senior Critic at the Yale School of Art.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] After negotiations with major publishers failed, Tufte decided to self-publish the book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* in 1982, working closely with graphic designer Howard Gralla.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte financed the work by taking out a second mortgage on his home.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] The book quickly became a commercial success and secured Tufte's transition from political scientist to information expert.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In 1999, after 22 years of service at Yale University, his professorship at Yale was made Emeritus.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] On March 5, 2010, President Barack Obama appointed Tufte to the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act's Recovery Independent Advisory Panel "to provide transparency in the use of Recovery-related funds".
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte is an expert in the presentation of infographics such as charts and diagrams, and is a fellow of the American Statistical Association.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He has held fellowships from the Guggenheim Foundation and the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte's writing is important in such fields as information design and visual literacy, which deal with the visual communication of information.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He coined the word *chartjunk* to refer to useless, non-informative, or information-obscuring elements of quantitative information displays.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte's other key concepts include what he calls the *lie factor*, the *data-ink ratio*, and the *data density* of a graphic.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte uses the term "data-ink ratio" to argue against using excessive decoration in visual displays of quantitative information.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In *Visual Display*, Tufte explains, "Sometimes decoration can help editorialize about the substance of the graphic.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte encourages the use of data-rich illustrations that present all available data.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] When such illustrations are examined closely, every data point has a value, but when they are looked at more generally, only trends and patterns can be observed.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte suggests these macro/micro readings be presented in the space of an eye-span, in the high resolution format of the printed page, and at the unhurried pace of the viewer's leisure.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte uses several historical examples to make his case.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] These include John Snow's cholera outbreak map, Charles Joseph Minard's *Carte Figurative*, early space debris plots, Galileo Galilei's *Sidereus Nuncius*, and Maya Lin's Vietnam Veterans Memorial.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] For instance, the listing of the names of deceased soldiers on the black granite of Lin's sculptural memorial is shown to be more powerful as a chronological list rather than as an alphabetical one.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] The sacrifice each fallen individual has made is thus highlighted within the overall time scope of the war.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In *Sidereus Nuncius*, Galileo presents the nightly observations of the moons of Jupiter in relation to the body itself, interwoven with the two-month narrative record.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte has criticized the way Microsoft PowerPoint is typically used.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte cites the way PowerPoint was used by NASA engineers in the events leading to the Space Shuttle Columbia disaster as an example of PowerPoint's many problems.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] The software style is designed to persuade rather than to inform people of technical details.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Instead, Tufte argues that the most effective way of presenting information in a technical setting, such as an academic seminar or a meeting of industry experts, is by distributing a brief written report that can be read by all participants in the first 5 to 10 minutes of the meeting.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte believes that this is the most efficient method of transferring knowledge from the presenter to the audience and then the rest of the meeting is devoted to discussion and debate.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] One method Tufte encourages to allow quick visual comparison of multiple series is the small multiple, a chart with many series shown on a single pair of axes that can often be easier to read when displayed as several separate pairs of axes placed next to each other.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] He suggests this is particularly helpful when the series are measured on quite different vertical (*y*-axis) scales, but over the same range on the horizontal *x*-axis (usually time).
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] These are often used as elements of a small multiple with several lines used together.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Tufte explains the sparkline as a kind of "word" that conveys rich information without breaking the flow of a sentence or paragraph made of other "words" both visual and conventional.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] To date, the earliest known implementation of sparklines was conceived by interaction designer Peter Zelchenko and implemented by programmer Mike Medved in early 1998.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Beyond his academic endeavors over the years, Tufte has created sculptures, often large outdoor ones made of metal or stone, that were first primarily exhibited on his own rural Connecticut property.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In 2009–10, some of these artworks were exhibited at the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum in Ridgefield, Connecticut, in the one-man show *Edward Tufte: Seeing Around*.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] Hogpen Hill Farms, the 234-acre (95-hectare) Tufte sculpture garden in Woodbury, Connecticut, is open to the public on summer weekends.
[src:chart-junk/edward-tufte] In 2010, Edward Tufte opened a gallery, ET Modern, in New York City's Chelsea Art District at 11th Avenue and 20th Street.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:chart-junk/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In statistics, a **misleading graph**, also known as a **distorted graph**, is a graph that misrepresents data, constituting a misuse of statistics and with the result that an incorrect conclusion may be derived from it.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs may be misleading by being excessively complex or poorly constructed.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Even when constructed to display the characteristics of their data accurately, graphs can be subject to different interpretations, or unintended kinds of data can seemingly and ultimately erroneously be derived.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Misleading graphs may be created intentionally to hinder the proper interpretation of data or accidentally due to unfamiliarity with graphing software, misinterpretation of data, or because data cannot be accurately conveyed.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Misleading graphs are often used in false advertising.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] One of the first authors to write about misleading graphs was Darrell Huff, publisher of the 1954 book *How to Lie with Statistics*.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] He has also highlighted the concentration of data scientists in employment by technology companies, which he believes can result in the hampering of the evaluation of their visualisations due to the proprietary and closed nature of much of the data they work with.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The field of data visualization describes ways to present information that avoids creating misleading graphs.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] There are numerous ways in which a misleading graph may be constructed.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The use of graphs where they are not needed can lead to unnecessary confusion/interpretation.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Generally, the more explanation a graph needs, the less the graph itself is needed.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs do not always convey information better than tables.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The use of biased or loaded words in the graph's title, axis labels, or caption may inappropriately prime the reader.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Similarly, attempting to draw trend lines through uncorrelated data may mislead the reader into believing a trend exists where there is none.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] This can be both the result of intentionally attempting to mislead the reader or due to the phenomenon of illusory correlation.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Comparing data on barcharts is generally much easier.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In the image below, it is very hard to tell where the blue sector is bigger than the green sector on the piecharts.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] A *perspective* (3D) pie chart is used to give the chart a 3D look.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Often used for aesthetic reasons, the third dimension does not improve the reading of the data; on the contrary, these plots are difficult to interpret because of the distorted effect of perspective associated with the third dimension.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The use of superfluous dimensions not used to display the data of interest is discouraged for charts in general, not only for pie charts.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In a 3D pie chart, the slices that are closer to the reader appear to be larger than those in the back due to the angle at which they're presented.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Item C appears to be at least as large as Item A in the misleading pie chart, whereas in actuality, it is less than half as large.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Item D looks a lot larger than item B, but they are the same size.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Using pictograms in bar graphs should not be scaled uniformly, as this creates a perceptually misleading comparison.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The area of the pictogram is interpreted instead of only its height or width.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] This causes the scaling to make the difference appear to be squared.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In the improperly scaled pictogram bar graph, the image for B is actually 9 times as large as A.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The perceived size increases when scaling.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The effect of improper scaling of pictograms is further exemplified when the pictogram has 3 dimensions, in which case the effect is cubed.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The graph of house sales (left) is misleading.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] It appears that home sales have grown eightfold in 2001 over the previous year, whereas they have actually grown twofold.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Besides, the number of sales is not specified.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] An improperly scaled pictogram may also suggest that the item itself has changed in size.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Assuming the pictures represent equivalent quantities, the misleading graph shows that there are more bananas because the bananas occupy the most area and are furthest to the right.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Logarithmic (or log) scales are a valid means of representing data.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] But when used without being clearly labeled as log scales or displayed to a reader unfamiliar with them, they can be misleading.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Log scales put the data values in terms of a chosen number (often 10) to a particular power.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] For example, log scales may give a height of 1 for a value of 10 in the data and a height of 6 for a value of 1,000,000 (106) in the data.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Log scales and variants are commonly used, for instance, for the volcanic explosivity index, the Richter scale for earthquakes, the magnitude of stars, and the pH of acidic and alkaline solutions.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Even in these cases, the log scale can make the data less apparent to the eye.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Often the reason for the use of log scales is that the graph's author wishes to display vastly different scales on the same axis.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Without log scales, comparing quantities such as 1000 (103) versus 109 (1,000,000,000) becomes visually impractical.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] A graph with a log scale that was not clearly labeled as such, or a graph with a log scale presented to a viewer who did not know logarithmic scales, would generally result in a representation that made data values look of similar size, in fact, being of widely differing magnitudes.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Misuse of a log scale can make vastly different values (such as 10 and 10,000) appear close together (on a base-10 log scale, they would be only 1 and 4).
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Or it can make small values appear to be negative due to how logarithmic scales represent numbers smaller than one.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Misuse of log scales may also cause relationships between quantities to appear linear whilst those relationships are exponentials or power laws that rise very rapidly towards higher values.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] It has been stated, although mainly in a humorous way, that "anything looks linear on a log-log plot with thick marker pen" .
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Both graphs show an identical exponential function of *f(x*) = 2*x*.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The graph on the left uses a linear scale, showing clearly an exponential trend.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The graph on the right, however uses a logarithmic scale, which generates a straight line.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] If the graph viewer were not aware of this, the graph would appear to show a linear trend.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] A **truncated graph** (also known as a **torn graph**) has a *y* axis that does not start at 0.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] These graphs can create the impression of important change where there is relatively little change.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] While truncated graphs can be used to overdraw differences or to save space, their use is often discouraged.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Commercial software such as MS Excel will tend to truncate graphs by default if the values are all within a narrow range, as in this example.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] To show relative differences in values over time, an index chart can be used.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Truncated diagrams will always distort the underlying numbers visually.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Several studies found that even if people were correctly informed that the y-axis was truncated, they still overestimated the actual differences, often substantially.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] These graphs display *identical data*; however, in the truncated bar graph on the left, the data *appear* to show significant differences, whereas, in the regular bar graph on the right, these differences are hardly visible.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Changing the *y*-axis maximum affects how the graph appears.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] A higher maximum will cause the graph to appear to have less volatility, less growth, and a less steep line than a lower maximum.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Changing the ratio of a graph's dimensions will affect how the graph appears.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The scales of a graph are often used to exaggerate or minimize differences.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The lack of a starting value for the *y* axis makes it unclear whether the graph is truncated.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Additionally, the lack of tick marks prevents the reader from determining whether the graph bars are properly scaled.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Without a scale, the visual difference between the bars can be easily manipulated.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Though all three graphs share the same data, and hence the actual slope of the (*x*, *y*) data is the same, the way that the data is plotted can change the visual appearance of the angle made by the line on the graph.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] This is because each plot has a different scale on its vertical axis.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Because the scale is not shown, these graphs can be misleading.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The intervals and units used in a graph may be manipulated to create or mitigate change expression.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs created with omitted data remove information from which to base a conclusion.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In the scatter plot with missing categories on the left, the growth appears to be more linear with less variation.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In financial reports, negative returns or data that do not correlate with a positive outlook may be excluded to create a more favorable visual impression.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The use of a superfluous third dimension, which does not contain information, is strongly discouraged, as it may confuse the reader.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs are designed to allow easier interpretation of statistical data.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] However, graphs with excessive complexity can obfuscate the data and make interpretation difficult.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Poorly constructed graphs can make data difficult to discern and thus interpret.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Misleading graphs may be used in turn to extrapolate misleading trends.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Several methods have been developed to determine whether graphs are distorted and to quantify this distortion.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] A graph with a high lie factor (>1) would exaggerate change in the data it represents, while one with a small lie factor (>0, <1) would obscure change in the data.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] A perfectly accurate graph would exhibit a lie factor of 1.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The **graph discrepancy index**, also known as the **graph distortion index** (**GDI**), was originally proposed by Paul John Steinbart in 1998.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] GDI is calculated as a percentage ranging from −100% to positive infinity, with zero percent indicating that the graph has been properly constructed and anything outside the ±5% margin is considered to be distorted.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Research into the usage of GDI as a measure of graphics distortion has found it to be inconsistent and discontinuous, making the usage of GDI as a measurement for comparisons difficult.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The data-ink ratio should be relatively high.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Otherwise, the chart may have unnecessary graphics.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The data density should be relatively high, otherwise a table may be better suited for displaying the data.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs are useful in the summary and interpretation of financial data.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs allow trends in large data sets to be seen while also allowing the data to be interpreted by non-specialists.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Graphs are often used in corporate annual reports as a form of impression management.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] In the United States, graphs do not have to be audited, as they fall under AU Section 550 Other Information in Documents Containing Audited Financial Statements.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Several published studies have looked at the usage of graphs in corporate reports for different corporations in different countries and have found frequent usage of improper design, selectivity, and measurement distortion within these reports.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The presence of misleading graphs in annual reports has led to requests for standards to be set.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Research has found that readers with poor levels of financial understanding have a greater chance of being misinformed by misleading graphs.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] Those with financial understanding, such as loan officers, may still be misled.
[src:chart-junk/misleading-graph] The perception of graphs is studied in psychophysics, cognitive psychology, and computational visions.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:chart-junk/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
